The paper deals with the problem of flocking control for mobile robots, which is a common topic in the field of robotics (cs.RO). The use of a Lyapunov-like function and graph theory for theoretical analysis suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of systems and control (cs.SY). The paper proposes a novel approach to distributed flocking control, which involves the use of a control protocol based on the information of neighbor mobile robots, indicating that the paper may also belong to the category of multiagent systems (cs.MA). The paper also mentions the objectives of velocity consensus, collision avoidance, and cohesion maintenance, which are common topics in the field of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the simulation results presented in the paper suggest that the paper may also belong to the category of machine learning (cs.LG).
